Core Technical Differences
Access Type:
NAS: Operates at the File Level. It manages its own file system and presents storage to users as a shared drive or folder (e.g., "Z: drive").
SAN: Operates at the Block Level. It presents raw storage blocks to a server, which the server’s operating system treats as a local, internal hard drive that it must format itself.
Connectivity:
NAS: Plugs directly into your existing Local Area Network (LAN) via standard Ethernet/TCP-IP.
SAN: Typically uses a dedicated, high-speed network separate from the LAN, often using Fibre Channel (FC) for maximum performance and low latency.
Protocols:
NAS: Common protocols include NFS (Unix/Linux), SMB/CIFS (Windows), and HTTP.
SAN: Uses SCSI, Fibre Channel, or iSCSI. 
